11/micro-on-nats.html)\n- Others?\n\nOpen questions:\n- What are the core abstractions and interfaces?\n- Is streaming significantly different than event sourcing and transport use cases?\n- What is the lowest common denominator for serialization?\n- Others?\n","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/go-kit/kit/issues/295/reactions","total_count":55,"+1":47,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":8,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/go-kit/kit/issues/295/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"completed","pinned_comment":null,"score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/github/securitylab/issues/379","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/github/securitylab","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/github/securitylab/issues/379/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/github/securitylab/issues/379/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/github/securitylab/issues/379/events","html_url":"https://github.com/github/securitylab/issues/379","id":910780844,"node_id":"MDU6SXNzdWU5MTA3ODA4NDQ=","number":379,"title":"[go]: Add query for detecting CORS misconfiguration","user":{"login":"gagliardetto","id":15271561,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjE1MjcxNTYx","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/15271561?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/gagliardetto","html_url":"https://github.com/gagliardetto","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gagliardetto/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gagliardetto/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gagliardetto/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gagliardetto/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gagliardetto/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gagliardetto/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gagliardetto/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gagliardetto/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gagliardetto/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"labels":[{"id":1671162472,"node_id":"MDU6TGFiZWwxNjcxMTYyNDcy","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/github/securitylab/labels/All%20For%20One","name":"All For One","color":"f75b99","default":false,"description":"Submissions to the All for One, One for All bounty"}],"state":"closed","locked":false,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":10,"created_at":"2021-06-03T19:13:18Z","updated_at":"2021-07-16T22:08:28Z","closed_at":"2021-07-16T22:02:33Z","assignee":null,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","issue_field_values":[],"type":null,"active_lock_reason":null,"sub_issues_summary":{"total":0,"completed":0,"percent_completed":0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"## Query\r\n\r\nRelevant PR: https://github.com/github/codeql-go/pull/542\r\n\r\n## CVE ID(s)\r\n\r\nNo CVEs.\r\n\r\n## Report\r\n\r\nAfter the addition of JavaScript to Netscape Navigator in 1995, it became necessary to introduce a security model that could limit the actions that an agent could undertake on behalf of the user. Before JavaScript, only the user could initiate actions.\r\n\r\nThe model that emerged is referred to as the \"same-origin policy\". Over time, many web-related technologies and vendors converged towards using some variant of it.\r\n\r\nBut as with many policies that regulate the web, over time, different needs and use-cases arise and require exceptions to those rules.\r\n\r\nIt's for that reason that the `Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS)` mechanism was introduced. The Same-Origin Policy and CORS are sets of rules that limit what defines an origin and what are the sub-resources that are accessible within that origin **or from an external origin**.\r\n\r\nAs many developers may testify, CORS is hardly the easiest or the most stable or consistent standard they had to deal with during their careers.\r\n\r\nCORS can be challenging with its limitations and confusing to the uninitiated. Frustration sometimes can lead to implementing solutions that open the doors to vulnerabilities.\r\n\r\nThis query targets exactly that: scenarios where the CORS permissions (for one reason or another) are *too permissive*.\r\n\r\n### Example Attack Scenario\r\n\r\nYou opened a new bank account at `myexamplebank.xyz`.\r\n\r\nFor some reason (maybe management, maybe regulation), there are multiple front-end subdomains in the format `{region}.myexamplebank.xyz` (in your case, it is `us.myexamplebank.xyz`), and there is only one API backend (`api.myexamplebank.xyz`).\r\n\r\nDifferent domains (and subdomains) count as different origins, which means that `api.myexamplebank.xyz` has to implement CORS in order to be reachable from the various front-end subdomains.\r\n\r\nWhen `us.myexamplebank.xyz` makes an API call to `api.myexamplebank.xyz`, your browser checks whether `api.myexamplebank.xyz` returns a CORS policy that allows it to be reached cross-origin from `us.myexamplebank.xyz`. If yes, then the request can go through, and you can successfully manage your bank account from `us.myexamplebank.xyz`.\r\n\r\nBehind the scenes, `api.myexamplebank.xyz` needs to reply with a `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: us.myexamplebank.xyz` header when hit with a preflight CORS request sent by the browser with the `OPTIONS` method (plus some other CORS headers, like `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`, which also allows sharing your cookies).\r\n\r\nBut the developers at your bank made a huge mistake (maybe because of continuous new regions that were added, or maybe because the CORS policies were too restrictive and continued to break the bank website as the browsers continue to slightly tweak the CORS rules and implementations, or maybe management just wanted so):\r\n\r\nThey made the CORS policy dependent on what the front-end request `Origin` header is, mirroring its value in the response `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header value.\r\n\r\nExamples:\r\n\r\n- For the `us.myexamplebank.xyz` origin, the `api.myexamplebank.xyz` will reply with `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: us.myexamplebank.xyz`.\r\n- For the `japan.myexamplebank.xyz` origin, the `api.myexamplebank.xyz` will reply with `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: japan.myexamplebank.xyz`.\r\n- For the `eu.myexamplebank.xyz` origin, the `api.myexamplebank.xyz` will reply with `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: eu.myexamplebank.xyz`.\r\n\r\nThe issue is that there were put no restrictions for this to happen:\r\n\r\n- For the `evil.com` origin, the `api.myexamplebank.xyz` will reply with `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: evil.com`.\r\n\r\nGotcha!\r\n\r\nThat opens up the doors for an attacker to transfer to themselves all your bank funds when you happen to load `evil.com` (or any other malicious domain), which will be allowed to access `api.myexamplebank.xyz` and make transactions on your behalf.\r\n\r\nYou might not even notice it while it is happening. You might be browsing the web and randomly end up on a malicious page that will want to access `api.myexamplebank.xyz` and leave you broke.\r\n\r\n- [ ] Are you planning to discuss this vulnerability submission publicly? (Blog Post, social networks, etc). *We would love to have you spread the word about the good work you are doing*\r\n\r\n## Result(s)\r\n\r\n*Provide at least one useful result found by your query, on some revision of a real project.*\r\n\r\n- [Example:](https://lgtm.com/projects/g/open-falcon/falcon-plus/snapshot/d1ed2b0d7be23d7fcf96aeeacd2ceb5c49a82ce2/files/modules/api/app/utils/auth_middle.go?sort=name&dir=ASC&mode=heatmap#xa2bda7035fbebcc1:1)\r\n    - The `CORS` function configures the CORS policy for all endpoint handlers, effectively being the one and only global CORS policy.\r\n\r\n## References\r\n\r\n- [Same-origin policy](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Security/Same-origin_policy)\r\n- [Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/CORS)\r\n- [RFC 6454: The Web Origin Concept](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc6454)\r\n- [WD-cors-20100727: Cross-Origin Resource Sharing](https://www.w3.org/TR/2010/WD-cors-20100727/)\r\n- [fetch: CORS protocol as it pertains to server developers](https://fetch.spec.whatwg.org/#cors-protocol)\r\n- [PortSwigger Web Security Academy on CORS](https://portswigger.net/web-security/cors)\r\n- [AppSec EU 2017 Exploiting CORS Misconfigurations For Bitcoins And Bounties by James Kettle](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wgkj4ZgxI4c)","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/github/securitylab/issues/379/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/github/securitylab/issues/379/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"completed","pinned_comment":null,"score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/atori74/streamsync-server/issues/17","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/atori74/streamsync-server","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/atori74/streamsync-server/issues/17/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/atori74/streamsync-server/issues/17/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/atori74/streamsync-server/issues/17/events","html_url":"https://github.com/atori74/streamsync-server/issues/17","id":881144951,"node_id":"MDU6SXNzdWU4ODExNDQ5NTE=","number":17,"title":"pubsubの実装","user":{"login":"atori74","id":36187588,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjM2MTg3NTg4","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/36187588?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/atori74","html_url":"https://github.com/atori74","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/atori74/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/atori74/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/